[[Image:Diana deutsch scale fig3b.jpg|350px|thumb|Deutsch's scale illusion.]]
Discovered by [[Diana Deutsch]] in 1973, '''Deutsch's "scale illusion"''' is an [[auditory illusion]] in which principles of grouping by [[frequency]], [[proximity space|proximity]], and spatial [[Sound localization|location]] are put into conflict and in which frequency proximity wins out.<ref>Bregman, Albert (1994). ''Auditory Scene Analysis: The Perceptual Organization of Sound'', p.76. {{ISBN|0-262-52195-4}}.</ref> It is produced by simultaneous ascending and descending [[major scale]]s beginning in separate [[stereophonic sound|stereo]] channels with each successive [[note (music)|note]] being switched to the opposite [[stereo channel|channel]]. With the left channel: C'-D-A-F--A-D-C'; and the right: C-B-E-G-E-B-C; the ear hears both: C'-B-A-G--A-B-C'; and: C-D-E-F--E-D-C. The tones are equal-amplitude [[sine wave]]s, and the sequence is played [[repeat sign|repeatedly]] without [[rest (music)|pause]] at a rate of four tones per second. (Listen to the Stereo Sound Example linked below.)
When listening to the illusion over [[headphone]]s, most [[handedness|right-handers]] hear a [[melody]] corresponding to the higher tones as on the right and a melody corresponding to the lower tones as on the left. When the earphone positions are reversed, the higher tones continue to appear to be coming from the right and the lower tones from the left. Other people experience different illusions, such as the higher tones on the left and the lower tones on the right, or a pattern in which the sounds appear to be localized in different and changing ways. [[Right-handedness|Right-handers]] and [[Left-handedness|left-handers]] differ statistically in how the scale illusion is perceived.
In a clinical study, patients with [[hemispatial neglect]] were shown to experience the scale illusion. Further, in an MEG study on normal listeners the scale illusion was found to be neurally represented at or near the auditory cortex.
{{Listen|filename=Deutsch scale illusion.ogg|title=Sound sample|description=The above example, played first a channel at a time, then simultaneously. The full illusion, as originally developed by Deutsch, is linked below.|format=[[Ogg]]}}
